Here's a simple C++ function that uses the `pugcpp` library (a C++ port of the popular `pug` template engine) to convert Markdown to HTML. Make sure to install `pugcpp` using your preferred package manager (e.g., `sudo apt-get install pugcpp` on Ubuntu-based systems).

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <pugcpp/pugcpp.hpp>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugcpp::config::set_path("templates");
    pugcpp::compiler compiler;

    // Create a Pug template for HTML output
    pugcpp::doc doc = compiler.compile("html");
    pugcpp::html Out = doc.out;

    // Render the Markdown text using the Pug template
    Out << markdown;
    std::string html = Out.str();

    return html;
}
```

In this example, I assume you have a `pugcpp` template file named `html.pug` with the following content:

```pug
html
  head
    title Markdown to HTML
  body
    #{markdown}
```

The `#` symbol in Pug is used for variable interpolation, so `#{markdown}` will replace the variable with the content of the `markdown` variable.

Call the `markdownToHtml` function like this:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello **World**!";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```html
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Markdown to HTML</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    Hello <strong>World</strong>!
  </body>
</html>
```

Note that you'll need to adjust the Pug template to fit your specific requirements for HTML output.

A classic! Coding the Snake game in C with smooth animation and images can be a challenging but rewarding project. Here's a high-level overview of how you can approach this:

**Requirements:**

* A C compiler (e.g., GCC)
* A graphics library (e.g., SDL, Allegro, or a simple console-based approach)
* Image files for the snake, apple, and background

**Step 1: Set up the project**

Create a new C project and include the necessary libraries and headers. For example, if using SDL, you'll need to:

```c
#include <SDL.h>
#include <SDL_image.h>
```

**Step 2: Initialize the game**

 Initialize the game window, set the title, and set the screen dimensions. You can also initialize the snake, apple, and background images.

```c
int main() {
    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        printf("SDL initialization failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return 1;
    }

    // Create a window
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", 100, 100, 640, 480, 0);
    if (!window) {
        printf("Window creation failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return 1;
    }

    // Set up the game loop
    bool running = true;
    while (running) {
        // Handle events
        SDL_Event event;
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                running = false;
            }
            // Other event handling (e.g., keyboard input)
        }

        // Update the game
        updateGame();

        // Render the game
        renderGame();

        // Update the screen
        SDL_RenderPresent(window);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
}
```

**Step 3: Update the game**

Implement the game logic, such as updating the snake's position, checking for collisions, and moving the apple.

```c
void updateGame() {
    // Update snake position
    snake_x += snake_dx;
    snake_y += snake_dy;

    // Check for collisions
    if (snake_x < 0 || snake_x >= 640 || snake_y < 0 || snake_y >= 480) {
        // Game over
    } else if (snake_x == apple_x && snake_y == apple_y) {
        // Eat the apple, grow the snake
        snake_length++;
    }

    // Update apple position
    if (snake_length > 0 && snake_x == apple_x && snake_y == apple_y) {
        apple_x = rand() % 640;
        apple_y = rand() % 480;
    }
}
```

**Step 4: Render the game**

Use the graphics library to render the game, including the snake, apple, and background images.

```c
void renderGame() {
    // Clear the screen
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(window->renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderClear(window->renderer);

    // Draw the background image
    SDL_Texture* background = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(window->renderer, background_image);
    SDL_RenderCopy(window->renderer, background, NULL, NULL);

    // Draw the snake
    for (int i = 0; i < snake_length; i++) {
        SDL_Rect snake_rect = {snake_x - snake_dx * i, snake_y - snake_dy * i, 20, 20};
        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(window->renderer, 255, 255, 255, 255);
        SDL_RenderFillRect(window->renderer, &snake_rect);
    }

    // Draw the apple
    SDL_Rect apple_rect = {apple_x, apple_y, 20, 20};
    SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(window->renderer, 255, 0, 0, 255);
    SDL_RenderFillRect(window->renderer, &apple_rect);

    // Update the screen
    SDL_RenderPresent(window->renderer);
}
```

**Step 5: Handle user input**

Implement keyboard input handling to move the snake left, right, up, or down.

```c
void handleInput() {
    if (SDL_GetKeyboardState(NULL)[SDL_SCANCODE_LEFT]) {
        snake_dx = -20;
        snake_dy = 0;
    } else if (SDL_GetKeyboardState(NULL)[SDL_SCANCODE_RIGHT]) {
        snake_dx = 20;
        snake_dy = 0;
    } else if (SDL_GetKeyboardState(NULL)[SDL_SCANCODE_UP]) {
        snake_dy = -20;
        snake_dx = 0;
    } else if (SDL_GetKeyboardState(NULL)[SDL_SCANCODE_DOWN]) {
        snake_dy = 20;
        snake_dx = 0;
    }
}
```

**Step 6: Use animation techniques**

To create a smooth animation, you can use various techniques such as:

* **Frame-based animation**: Divide the game into frames, and update the game state only when a frame is complete.
* **Delta-time-based animation**: Update the game state based on the time elapsed since the last frame.
* **Interpolation**: Smoothly interpolate the game state between frames using mathematical functions.

For example, you can use the following function to update the snake's position based on the time elapsed since the last frame:

```c
void updateSnakePosition(float dt) {
    snake_x += snake_dx * dt;
    snake_y += snake_dy * dt;
}
```

**Step 7: Handle game over**

Implement a game over logic when the snake collides with the boundary or itself.

```c
void gameOver() {
    // Game over message
    printf("Game Over!\n");

    // Reset the game state
    snake_length = 0;
    snake_dx = 0;
    snake_dy = 0;
    snake_x = 0;
    snake_y = 0;
    apple_x = 0;
    apple_y = 0;
}
```

This is a basic outline of how you can create a smooth Snake game in C using images and animations. You'll need to implement more features, such as scoring, level design, and sound effects, to make the game more engaging.

